               <interp inst="t18470510-1282" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18470510"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18470510-1282" type="date" value="18470510"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18470510-1282-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1282-18470510 t18470510-1282-offence-1 t18470510-1282-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1282. <persName id="def1-1282-18470510" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1282-18470510" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1282-18470510" type="age" value="38"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1282-18470510" type="surname" value="CLARKE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1282-18470510" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN CLARKE</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18470510-1282-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470510-1282-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470510-1282-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> for stealing 129 sovereigns, and 55 half-sovereigns; the monies of <persName id="t18470510-name-1053" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1053" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1053" type="surname" value="TRUMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1053" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18470510-1282-offence-1 t18470510-name-1053"></join>Sarah Truman</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HUDDLESTON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470510-name-1054" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1054" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1054" type="surname" value="TRUMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1054" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>SARAH TRUMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Kepple-street, and keep a beer-shop—I have been living with the prisoner for some years as his wife—before I lived with him, I had about 200<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in my possession—I paid 40<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. of it to go into the house which I live in—I had got this money at various times in service, and liv<lb></lb>ing as housekeeper with Mr. Scott—the prisoner did not know I was possessed✗</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184705100186"></xptr>
               <p>of this money—on the 6th of May, I went out for the whole day—I returned home about a quarter-past twelve o'clock in the evening—the prisoner was not at home—he came home at past two o'clock—on the afternoon of the next day, I missed his hat-box, and then his coat and all his clothes—I then looked at my box, and found it had been broken open—I missed a green purse, containing money—I asked the prisoner if he had taken away his clothes himself—he said, he had not, but Mr. Parker (who lodged in the house) had taken out a bundle last night, at six o'clock—I gave him in charge, for✗ stealing my purse—I went with him to the police-station—the inspector refused to take the charge—I was desired to go home, and look the place over—I missed another bag, containing money, when I came home—I missed altogether, more than one hundred sovereigns, and some half-sovereigns—I gave the prisoner in charge again—I went on the Saturday to Montpelier-row, and found the whole of my property, 156<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in sovereigns and half-sovereigns</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRAEN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You did not know till you found it, how much had lost? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I knew by what I had taken from it, what I had left—I have been living with the prisoner between four and five years—I have kept the beer-shop about three years—the prisoner is a labourer<lb></lb>he works at one thing or another—he was employed in a cow-shed when I first knew him—he had 18<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a-week—he did not bring his wages home—what he brought home was very little—it went in support of house—he worked, at times, after the beer-house was taken—after he came from work he might have attended a little to the business—he never paid money, he might take have money—I had lodgers in the house—I sometimes received 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.✗ or 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a-week from them, sometimes less—I could not save any of that—I took some from the money I had saved—I never added any to it for four years—I could not tell to a sovereign or two what I had there—the money was in the purse four years ago—this bag is one that I have had about two years—I look some money from one, and put it into the other—on the Friday, after the charge was dismissed, he held up a bag tome and said, "I have got your money"—he said, "You had a <hi rend="italic">spree</hi> last night, I will have one to<lb></lb>night"—I had no means of living except what I took from the lodgers, and the proceeds of the beer-shop—I paid 27<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a-year rent, and the license was 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a-year—the prisoner paid the license—I gave him the money to pay it with—I paid the rent—the receipts were not in my name.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HUDDLESTONE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You say when he came back he held up a bag to you, and said he had got your money? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; that was after he had been to the inspector and had the charge dismissed—in the morning I had said to him, "Will you have the kindness to clean the pots to-day"—he said, "No; I will never clean another pot as long as I live—my name is <hi rend="italic">Walker</hi> "—he said, "I have got plenty of money, I am going to enjoy my<lb></lb>self"—that was before I had missed the money—when I charged him with taking my money, he said he knew nothing at all of it, nor yet of his clothes—he said he did not know I was possessed of a farthing, and when he came back from the inspector he pulled out a small bag in which he carried his own money, and thrust it at me and said, "There is your b——y money, you got it out of b——y old Scott"—I had all this money before I went to live with the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you swear positively that you had all these sovereigns before you lived with the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do; and none of them were got in our joint concern after we were living together.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470510-name-1055" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1055" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1055" type="surname" value="HERBERT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1055" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE HERBERT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a <hi rend="italic">cab</hi> man. I was with my <hi rend="italic">cab</hi> at the Admiral Keppel stand on the night of Thursday, 6th May—the prisoner came to me From twelve to half-past twelve o'clock at night; he got into the <hi rend="italic">cab</hi>, and I drove</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184705100187"></xptr>
               <p>him to Montpelier-row, Hammersmith—I took a hat-box and a bundle there—I brought the prisoner back to Collage-street, Chelsea—he asked me what my fare was, I said 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—he paid me, and he said, "Here is 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. more, if you know nothing"—that was 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. over my fare—I afterwards saw the same bundle opened, and there were 156 sovereigns in it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> What house did you leave it in? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> In the middle house in Montpelier-row, on the right hand—I did not know the prisoner before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470510-name-1056" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1056" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1056" type="surname" value="MURRAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1056" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN MURRAY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable B</hi> 223.) I was present at the opening of the bundle—William Henry Edwards lives in the house, in Montpelier-row—he told me he was a basket-marker.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
